<br>
What does the 50/50 bring to the table? Well as said before, more WeaponSkill, a bit higher based damage, higher Flurry damage, more off hand swings, and the raw utility of having every style to use.<br>
<br>
To anwser your question about styles specificly, Amy. Slash + Diamond Slash brings huge To Hit pluses in an anytime style chain that has very solid damage. Does it drink End? Yes, but that's the price to pay for using a style that almost guarentees a hit with solid bonus damage in any situation. I personally really like the hits Diamond Slash does (Especially after RR 5+) and anyone who says it doesn't hit hard isn't paying attention. One Paladin, and <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>always</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> carry 3-5 80% End Heal potions, and the End problems all but vanish in PvE and RvR. Since it's only the longest fights that'll drain it all, especially in RvR.<br>
<br>
Dual Shadows brings reduced End and a nasty Bleed (18-30 damage a tick, depending on Body resist, for 7 ticks) with solid damage (More then Amy. Slash, less the Diamond) to anything that dares face you one-on-one. In small 1-2 vs. 1-2 RvR group fights, adding this to the first swat you give someone is nice, and keeps pesky speed classes from getting away. For PvE, this style is a must for the Merc', if only for the bleed. On high end mobs, where every tank in the group is lucky if they are hitting for 50 damage a swat, there's Dual Shadows giving you +50% damage with its +25 damage Bleed, every hit. On lower mobs you may be soloing, it's like having a Damage Add on all the time, and even stacks with them. But i agree it should have its Med. Defense Penilty removed.<br>
<br>
And you want to give up all that for maybe an extra 10% to Parry? 28 + 15 + MoParry 1-2 will give you a 49 to 55 effective Parry, and has been plenty from everything i've seen.<br>
<br>
